Supervised Learning Regression Project: Cars4U¶

Data Dictionary

S.No.: Serial number

Name: Name of the car which includes brand name and model name

Location: Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)

Year: Manufacturing year of the car

Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers (a unit used to measure length or distance) driven in the car by the previous owner(s)

Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)

Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)

Owner: Type of ownership

Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg

Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC

Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp

Seats: The number of seats in the car

New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)

Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

# km/kg to kmpl conversion
def kmpl(km_per_kg, density):
    kmpl = km_per_kg / density
    return kmpl

# kmpl to mpg conversion
def kmpl_to_mpg(kmpl):
    mpg = kmpl * 2.35214583
    return mpg


# km/kg to mpg conversion
def km_to_mpg(km_per_kg):
    mpg = km_per_kg * 2.82481
    return mpg

# apply conversion functions using apply method
df.loc[df['Mileage_unit'] == 'kmpl', 'Mileage_value'] = df.loc[df['Mileage_unit'] == 'kmpl', 'Mileage_value'].apply(lambda x: kmpl_to_mpg(x))
df.loc[df['Mileage_unit'] == 'km/kg', 'Mileage_value'] = df.loc[df['Mileage_unit'] == 'km/kg', 'Mileage_value'].apply(lambda x: km_to_mpg(x))

Since Price represents the price of a Used car, I first assumed it was because those cars with null values were new, but that can't be the case because we have cars that were previously owned and a few years old with null values

I have a couple of options

  1. I could just fill the nulls values for the New cars with the New Price
  2. I could drop the Price column all together, but I am interested to see any interesting data that may come up for the used car price
  3. I could drop the rows where the Price is null, but then I would miss out on an opportunity for some good data
  4. I could replace the null values with the average, median or mode for Used car price

I think I will take aproach 4, but I'll first look at how the Price data is distributed to see which fill method will be the best

#IQR

def treat_outliers(df, col):
    """
    treats outliers in a variable
    col: str, name of the numerical variable
    df: dataframe
    col: name of the column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1                # Inter Quantile Range (75th perentile - 25th percentile)
    lower_whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # all the values smaller than lower_whisker will be assigned the value of lower_whisker
    # all the values greater than upper_whisker will be assigned the value of upper_whisker
    # the assignment will be done by using the clip function of NumPy
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], lower_whisker, upper_whisker)

    return df

#check the outliers

#Treating outliers in Rooms column

df = treat_outliers(df,'Price')
df = treat_outliers(df,'New_Price')

import pandas as pd


# Compute the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = df.corr()

# Filter out variables with correlation coefficients above 50% or below -50%
high_corr_vars = corr_matrix[abs(corr_matrix) > 0.2].stack().reset_index()
high_corr_vars = high_corr_vars[high_corr_vars['level_0'] != high_corr_vars['level_1']]
high_corr_vars = high_corr_vars.drop_duplicates(subset=[0])
high_corr_vars.columns = ['Variable 1', 'Variable 2', 'Correlation']
high_corr_vars = high_corr_vars.sort_values(by='Correlation', ascending=False)

corr_list = high_corr_vars[['Variable 1', 'Variable 2']].values.flatten().tolist()
corr_list = list(set(corr_list))

#Remove Price because that is what we are going to use to predict
corr_list.remove('Price')

# Print the variables that have correlation coefficients above 20% or below -20%

from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn import linear_model


#The below adds a bunch of new variables which WILL increase the R^2 value.  Adding more variables will always increas
#the R^2 but will not always improve the model.  See how the training R^2 jumps up to 90% but the test set only goe sup
#by 2 points to 86%
poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, interaction_only=True)
X_train2 = poly.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test2 = poly.fit_transform(X_test)

poly_clf = linear_model.LinearRegression()

poly_clf.fit(X_train2, y_train)

y_pred = poly_clf.predict(X_test2)

#print(y_pred)

#In sample (training) R^2 will always improve with the number of variables!
print(poly_clf.score(X_train2, y_train))

#Using Adjusted R^2

# Calculate the adjusted R-squared value
n = len(X_test)
k = len(X_train.columns)
r2 = regression_model.score(X_train, y_train)
r2_adj = 1 - (1 - r2) * ((n - 1) / (n - k - 1))
